  "notes": [
    {
      "id": "note_6",
      "text": "WORKFLOW: compare several groups (one-way ANOVA). With three or more conditions you cannot just run many t-tests — that inflates the false-positive rate. Compare groups on 'auto' runs the omnibus test first (one-way ANOVA when the groups look normal, Kruskal-Wallis otherwise): a single test of 'do ANY of the groups differ?'. ONLY if that omnibus p is significant do you read the post-hoc pairwise grid (Tukey-Kramer / Holm-adjusted), which controls the family-wise error across the comparisons and tells you WHICH pairs differ. The mean ± SEM plot shows the group means and their precision; the boxplot with significance bars shows the full distributions and the significant pairs. Read top-down: omnibus → (if significant) post-hoc → effect direction. Fisher (1925); Tukey (1949); Kruskal & Wallis (1952).",
      "x": 40,
      "y": 24,
      "width": 360,
      "height": 190
    }
